05312nam a22008535i 9780823265503DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20152015nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232655037 a10.1515/97808232655032doi  a(DE-B1597)555055  a(OCoLC)913704589  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aHIS0430002bisacsh04a840.9/3584053182231 aSanyal, Debarati, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMemory and Complicity :bMigrations of Holocaust Remembrance /cDebarati Sanyal. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Pathways of Memory, Dangerous Intersections -- t1. A Soccer Match in Auschwitz: Passing Trauma in Holocaust Studies -- t2. Concentrationary Migrations in and around Albert Camus -- t3. Auschwitz as Allegory: From Night and Fog to Guantánamo Bay -- t4. Crabwalk History: Torture, Allegory, and Memory in Sartre -- t5. Reading Nazi Memory in Jonathan Littell’s The Kindly Ones -- t6. Holocaust and Colonial Memory in the Age of Terror: Assia Djebar and Boualem Sansal -- tAfterword -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince World War II, French and Francophone literature and film have repeatedly sought not to singularize the Holocaust as the paradigm of historical trauma but rather to connect its memory with other memories of violence, namely that of colonialism. These works produced what Debarati Sanyal calls a “memory-in-complicity” attuned to the gray zones that implicate different regimes of violence across history as well as those of different subject positions such as victim, perpetrator, witness, and reader/spectator. Examining a range of works from Albert Camus, Primo Levi, Alain Resnais, and Jean-Paul Sartre to Jonathan Littell, Assia Djebar, Giorgio Agamben, and Boualem Sansal, Memory and Complicity develops an inquiry into the political force and ethical dangers of such implications, contrasting them with contemporary models for thinking about trauma and violence and offering an extended meditation on the role of aesthetic form, especially allegory, within acts of transhistorical remembrance. What are the political benefits and ethical risks of invoking the memory of one history in order to address another? What is the role of complicity in making these connections? How does complicity, rather than affect based discourses of trauma, shame and melancholy, open a critical engagement with the violence of history? What is it about literature and film that have made them such powerful vehicles for this kind of connective memory work?As it offers new readings of some of the most celebrated and controversial novelists, filmmakers, and playwrights from the French-speaking world, Memory and Complicity addresses these questions in order to reframe the way we think about historical memory and its political uses today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aArtxPolitical aspects. 0aCollective memoryzFrance. 0aCollective memoryzFrench-speaking countries. 0aColonizationxSocial aspects. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)xHistoriography. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945), in literature. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945), in motion pictures. 0aViolencexSocial aspects. 7aHISTORY / Holocaust.2bisacsh  aAlgeria.  aAllegory.  aMemory.  acomplicity.  aethics.  afrance.  atransculturual.  atransnational.  atrauma.  aviolence.  awitness.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311072903040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823265503zCo-access DOI